WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.485 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.485 --> 00:00:04.473 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.473 --> 00:00:07.952 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.952 --> 00:00:15.852 align:middle line:90%


00:00:15.852 --> 00:00:18.060 align:middle line:84%
CASEY RODRIGUES: So I'm
going to prove a few theorems

00:00:18.060 --> 00:00:22.200 align:middle line:84%
about limits, which will
allow us to compute limits,

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:29.920 align:middle line:84%
or at least we can use to prove
that other non-trivial limits

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:32.950 align:middle line:84%
exist using these
theorems, rather than using

00:00:32.950 --> 00:00:34.850 align:middle line:90%
the definition directly.

00:00:34.850 --> 00:00:43.720 align:middle line:84%
So this first theorem is the
easiest theorem in the world

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:47.440 align:middle line:84%
because it's simply just
restating the definition

00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:49.670 align:middle line:90%
of convergence of a sequence.

00:00:49.670 --> 00:00:57.640 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to state it as
follows, so pretty short,

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:02.710 align:middle line:84%
that if I have a
sequence x sub n,

00:01:02.710 --> 00:01:12.790 align:middle line:84%
then it converges to x if and
only if the sequence obtained

00:01:12.790 --> 00:01:19.320 align:middle line:84%
by taking the absolute value
of x of n minus x equals 0,

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:22.020 align:middle line:84%
or the limit of
that sequence is 0.

00:01:22.020 --> 00:01:24.630 align:middle line:90%
So what is the proof?

00:01:24.630 --> 00:01:27.730 align:middle line:84%
It follows just immediately
from the definition.

00:01:27.730 --> 00:01:29.850 align:middle line:84%
So I'm not even going
to write anything.

00:01:29.850 --> 00:01:30.870 align:middle line:90%
I'll leave it to you.

00:01:30.870 --> 00:01:34.590 align:middle line:90%


00:01:34.590 --> 00:01:40.650 align:middle line:84%
But the proof follows from the
definition and the simple fact

00:01:40.650 --> 00:01:45.900 align:middle line:84%
that x sub n minus
x in absolute value

00:01:45.900 --> 00:01:51.710 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the absolute value
of the absolute value of x sub

00:01:51.710 --> 00:01:54.940 align:middle line:90%
n minus x minus 0, OK.

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:59.590 align:middle line:84%
So the definition says
for all epsilon positive,

00:01:59.590 --> 00:02:02.380 align:middle line:84%
you have to find an M so that
this is less than epsilon

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:04.570 align:middle line:84%
for all m bigger than
or equal to capital M.

00:02:04.570 --> 00:02:08.080 align:middle line:84%
But if you found such a
capital M for this to be less

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:09.729 align:middle line:84%
than epsilon, then
this will be less

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:13.690 align:middle line:84%
than epsilon, which is saying
that this limit equals 0.

00:02:13.690 --> 00:02:17.030 align:middle line:84%
And then going the other
direction, it's the same thing.

00:02:17.030 --> 00:02:19.060 align:middle line:84%
So this is just
following directly

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:24.460 align:middle line:84%
from the definition
and this simple fact.

00:02:24.460 --> 00:02:28.150 align:middle line:84%
OK, that was a very
silly fact about limits,

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:31.510 align:middle line:84%
but a very useful
one in conjunction

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:37.742 align:middle line:84%
with the next theorem,
which is not so trivial,

00:02:37.742 --> 00:02:38.950 align:middle line:90%
which is the squeeze theorem.

00:02:38.950 --> 00:02:45.750 align:middle line:90%


00:02:45.750 --> 00:02:47.460 align:middle line:90%
And it says the following.

00:02:47.460 --> 00:03:03.630 align:middle line:84%
So let an, bn, and
xn be sequences such

00:03:03.630 --> 00:03:08.650 align:middle line:84%
that the following
holds for all n

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:12.370 align:middle line:84%
natural numbers, a
sub n is less than

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:17.140 align:middle line:84%
or equal x sub n is less
than or equal to b sub n.

00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:29.790 align:middle line:84%
And a sub n and b sub n
are convergent sequences.

00:03:29.790 --> 00:03:32.660 align:middle line:90%


00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:39.590 align:middle line:84%
And their limits
equal each other.

00:03:39.590 --> 00:03:41.720 align:middle line:84%
And they're given by
some number, call it x.

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:44.820 align:middle line:90%


00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:55.700 align:middle line:84%
Then the conclusion
is that the limit as n

00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:57.800 align:middle line:84%
goes to infinity of
x sub n equals x.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:01.100 align:middle line:84%
So when I write something like
this, you should also kind of--

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:05.090 align:middle line:84%
there's half a sentence
before that that

00:04:05.090 --> 00:04:08.810 align:middle line:84%
goes with this saying, x of
n is a conversion sequence.

00:04:08.810 --> 00:04:10.880 align:middle line:90%
And its limit is equal to x.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:14.180 align:middle line:84%
So it's two statements
in one when I write that.

00:04:14.180 --> 00:04:18.410 align:middle line:90%


00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:25.610 align:middle line:84%
So if you just draw a
picture, the squeezed theorem

00:04:25.610 --> 00:04:27.110 align:middle line:90%
shouldn't be too surprising.

00:04:27.110 --> 00:04:33.870 align:middle line:90%


00:04:33.870 --> 00:04:38.010 align:middle line:90%
So this is a little discussion.

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:44.370 align:middle line:84%
So here's x, the common
limit of a sub n and b sub n.

00:04:44.370 --> 00:04:49.770 align:middle line:84%
And so we can imagine that we're
trying to show the limit as n

00:04:49.770 --> 00:04:51.720 align:middle line:84%
goes to infinity of
x sub n equals x.

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:55.770 align:middle line:84%
So that means we have to find
for every epsilon a capital M

00:04:55.770 --> 00:04:59.940 align:middle line:84%
so that x sub n is
between x plus epsilon

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:02.880 align:middle line:90%
and x minus epsilon.

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:07.370 align:middle line:84%
So if I go out a
little bit, I would

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:08.880 align:middle line:84%
hope I can find
a natural number,

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:15.350 align:middle line:84%
a capital M so that
x sub n minus x--

00:05:15.350 --> 00:05:18.230 align:middle line:84%
or x sub n is in
this little interval.

00:05:18.230 --> 00:05:22.595 align:middle line:84%
Now, if I'm assuming that a
sub n and x sub n, if a sub n

00:05:22.595 --> 00:05:26.120 align:middle line:84%
and b sub n are squeezing
x sub n, in other words x

00:05:26.120 --> 00:05:32.450 align:middle line:84%
sub n is between the two, and b
sub n is converging to x, then

00:05:32.450 --> 00:05:38.450 align:middle line:84%
for n bigger than or
equal to some integer M0,

00:05:38.450 --> 00:05:41.603 align:middle line:84%
all of the b sub n's
are in this interval.

00:05:41.603 --> 00:05:42.770 align:middle line:90%
OK, maybe they're not there.

00:05:42.770 --> 00:05:45.200 align:middle line:90%
Maybe they could be over here.

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:47.660 align:middle line:84%
But the way I drew it is
just to the right of x.

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:52.850 align:middle line:84%
And, likewise, since a
sub n is converging to x,

00:05:52.850 --> 00:05:57.470 align:middle line:84%
there exists some
other integer M sub 1

00:05:57.470 --> 00:06:02.240 align:middle line:84%
so that if I look at a sub n,
it's also in this interval.

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:03.230 align:middle line:90%
Maybe it's over here.

00:06:03.230 --> 00:06:06.890 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's-- well, it can't
be to the right of b sub n

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:11.480 align:middle line:84%
because that inequality up there
strictly implies that a sub n

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:14.480 align:middle line:84%
is less than or
equal to b sub n.

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:18.100 align:middle line:90%
But it's in this interval.

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:21.580 align:middle line:84%
So then what would
that say if I look

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:29.550 align:middle line:84%
at n bigger than or equal to
n plus M1, M0 plus M1, then n

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:32.940 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than M0, this guy.

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:36.060 align:middle line:84%
And n is bigger than
both and M1, this guy.

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:37.560 align:middle line:84%
And therefore if
I look at x sub n,

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:40.212 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be
between these two.

00:06:40.212 --> 00:06:42.420 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, it's
going to be in this interval.

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:45.030 align:middle line:90%


00:06:45.030 --> 00:06:47.010 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
proof in a picture.

00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:51.810 align:middle line:84%
And now our goal is
just to write it down.

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:54.070 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
picture of the proof.

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:57.210 align:middle line:84%
But if you're actually trying
to guess why this would be true?

00:06:57.210 --> 00:06:58.840 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the b sub
n's, you can imagine,

00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:01.470 align:middle line:90%
are getting very close to x.

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:04.365 align:middle line:84%
The a sub n's are also
getting very close to x.

00:07:04.365 --> 00:07:06.240 align:middle line:84%
x sub n is in between
the two, so it's

00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:09.540 align:middle line:84%
getting squeezed to
x, and thus the name.

00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:24.730 align:middle line:90%


00:07:24.730 --> 00:07:30.340 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now we just need to
turn this into written word.

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:31.450 align:middle line:90%
So we need to show--

00:07:31.450 --> 00:07:35.440 align:middle line:84%
we're going to show that
x sub n converges to x.

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:39.520 align:middle line:84%
So we're-- all we have is
an epsilon delta proof.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:41.410 align:middle line:90%
Or we could use that theorem.

00:07:41.410 --> 00:07:44.740 align:middle line:84%
But let's go with an
epsilon delta proof.

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:49.750 align:middle line:84%
I mean, not epsilon delta,
epsilon M. Epsilon delta proofs

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:52.090 align:middle line:90%
will come later.

00:07:52.090 --> 00:07:55.130 align:middle line:90%
So let epsilon be positive.

00:07:55.130 --> 00:08:01.210 align:middle line:84%
And since b sub n
converges to x, there

00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:07.060 align:middle line:84%
exist to M0 in natural numbers
such that for all n bigger

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:18.040 align:middle line:84%
than or equal to n sub 0, b sub
n minus x is less than epsilon

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:29.748 align:middle line:84%
in absolute value, which is
the same as saying-- well,

00:08:29.748 --> 00:08:30.790 align:middle line:90%
I mean it's not the same.

00:08:30.790 --> 00:08:35.320 align:middle line:84%
But it implies that b sub n
is less than x plus epsilon.

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:41.620 align:middle line:90%


00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:45.220 align:middle line:84%
Since a sub n's
converge to x as well,

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:49.720 align:middle line:84%
there exists a M sub
1, natural number,

00:08:49.720 --> 00:08:57.310 align:middle line:84%
such that for all n
bigger than or equal M1,

00:08:57.310 --> 00:08:59.380 align:middle line:84%
a sub n minus x
in absolute value

00:08:59.380 --> 00:09:02.830 align:middle line:84%
is less than epsilon,
which implies

00:09:02.830 --> 00:09:06.520 align:middle line:84%
a sub n is between x minus
epsilon and x plus epsilon,

00:09:06.520 --> 00:09:09.460 align:middle line:84%
but I'm only going to use
one of those inequalities.

00:09:09.460 --> 00:09:19.760 align:middle line:90%


00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:22.640 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm going to choose the
capital M for my sequence

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:25.640 align:middle line:84%
x sub n, I'm trying to
show convergence to x.

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:30.590 align:middle line:84%
So choose m to be m
sub-zero plus M sub 1.

00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:33.770 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you could have chosen
it to be the maximum of the two.

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:35.525 align:middle line:84%
But this works
just fine as well.

00:09:35.525 --> 00:09:38.390 align:middle line:90%


00:09:38.390 --> 00:09:45.110 align:middle line:84%
Then if n is bigger
than or equal to m,

00:09:45.110 --> 00:09:49.690 align:middle line:84%
this implies n is bigger
than or equal to M0

00:09:49.690 --> 00:09:53.180 align:middle line:84%
and M is bigger than
or equal to M1, which

00:09:53.180 --> 00:09:55.880 align:middle line:84%
implies that both of
these inequalities

00:09:55.880 --> 00:09:59.950 align:middle line:90%
here are valid for this n.

00:09:59.950 --> 00:10:04.480 align:middle line:84%
So then x minus epsilon is
less than a sub n, which

00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:13.970 align:middle line:84%
by assumption, is less than
or equal to x sub n, which

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:18.110 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to b
sub n, which is less than x

00:10:18.110 --> 00:10:20.160 align:middle line:90%
plus epsilon.

00:10:20.160 --> 00:10:21.590 align:middle line:84%
Now, these string
of inequalities,

00:10:21.590 --> 00:10:23.660 align:middle line:84%
therefore, tell us
that x minus epsilon

00:10:23.660 --> 00:10:27.650 align:middle line:84%
is less than x sub
n is less than x

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:34.990 align:middle line:84%
plus epsilon, which is
equivalent to saying

00:10:34.990 --> 00:10:40.520 align:middle line:84%
the absolute value of x, so then
minus x is less than epsilon.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:45.115 align:middle line:84%
And therefore x sub
n converges to x.

00:10:45.115 --> 00:10:52.620 align:middle line:90%


00:10:52.620 --> 00:11:07.090 align:middle line:84%
So these two facts together give
us a very robust and short way

00:11:07.090 --> 00:11:10.180 align:middle line:90%
to prove limits of sequences.

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:15.170 align:middle line:90%


00:11:15.170 --> 00:11:20.090 align:middle line:84%
So, for example, let me
give you a simple one.

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:37.420 align:middle line:90%


00:11:37.420 --> 00:11:40.560 align:middle line:84%
Let's show the limit as n goes
to infinity of n squared over n

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:46.800 align:middle line:90%
squared plus n plus 1 equals 1.

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:49.800 align:middle line:84%
So, I mean, this is
a very simple limit

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:51.220 align:middle line:90%
to use these theorems on.

00:11:51.220 --> 00:11:53.970 align:middle line:84%
But in practice,
you don't always

00:11:53.970 --> 00:11:55.830 align:middle line:84%
have just a simple
expression like this.

00:11:55.830 --> 00:12:02.772 align:middle line:90%


00:12:02.772 --> 00:12:04.730 align:middle line:84%
And we'll use these two
theorems in conjunction

00:12:04.730 --> 00:12:06.647 align:middle line:84%
to prove some other
theorems here in a minute.

00:12:06.647 --> 00:12:09.270 align:middle line:84%
But let's just see
it in action once.

00:12:09.270 --> 00:12:11.980 align:middle line:90%
Let me look at--

00:12:11.980 --> 00:12:16.510 align:middle line:84%
so this sequence
converges to 1 if and only

00:12:16.510 --> 00:12:19.690 align:middle line:84%
if the absolute value of the
difference converges to 0.

00:12:19.690 --> 00:12:23.080 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at the absolute
value of the difference.

00:12:23.080 --> 00:12:28.030 align:middle line:90%


00:12:28.030 --> 00:12:30.460 align:middle line:84%
This is equal to-- now
just doing the algebra--

00:12:30.460 --> 00:12:31.510 align:middle line:90%
this is equal to--

00:12:31.510 --> 00:12:35.740 align:middle line:90%


00:12:35.740 --> 00:12:43.190 align:middle line:84%
and taking absolute
values gives me n plus 1

00:12:43.190 --> 00:12:48.600 align:middle line:90%
over n squared plus n plus 1.

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:50.520 align:middle line:84%
And this is less
than or equal to.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:53.430 align:middle line:84%
This 1 is making things
bigger, so I can drop it.

00:12:53.430 --> 00:12:56.700 align:middle line:84%
And this is less than
or equal to n plus 1

00:12:56.700 --> 00:12:59.340 align:middle line:90%
over n squared plus n.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:03.570 align:middle line:84%
Now, n squared plus n I can
factor into n times n plus 1.

00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:07.990 align:middle line:84%
So then that cancels with
this n plus 1 on top.

00:13:07.990 --> 00:13:09.360 align:middle line:90%
And I just get 1 over n.

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:11.970 align:middle line:90%


00:13:11.970 --> 00:13:18.540 align:middle line:84%
So 0 is less than or equal
to n squared over n squared

00:13:18.540 --> 00:13:25.900 align:middle line:84%
plus n plus 1 minus 1, which is
less than or equal to 1 over n.

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:29.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, 1 over n we've shown
using epsilon delta proof--

00:13:29.410 --> 00:13:31.040 align:middle line:90%
I mean, epsilon M proof.

00:13:31.040 --> 00:13:34.840 align:middle line:84%
We've shown 1 over
n converges to 0.

00:13:34.840 --> 00:13:42.070 align:middle line:84%
So since 0 converges
to 0, the left side,

00:13:42.070 --> 00:13:46.310 align:middle line:84%
and 1 over n converges
to 0, the right side,

00:13:46.310 --> 00:13:50.330 align:middle line:84%
that implies by the
squeeze theorem,

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:54.640 align:middle line:84%
n squared over n squared plus
n plus 1 minus 1 converges

00:13:54.640 --> 00:14:01.370 align:middle line:90%
to 0 by the squeeze theorem.

00:14:01.370 --> 00:14:05.720 align:middle line:84%
Which implies that
n squared over n

00:14:05.720 --> 00:14:09.980 align:middle line:84%
squared plus n plus 1 converges
to 1 by that first theorem.

00:14:09.980 --> 00:14:18.250 align:middle line:90%


00:14:18.250 --> 00:14:24.450 align:middle line:84%
OK now you can imagine
that instead of having this

00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:32.630 align:middle line:84%
at your disposal, I asked
you to do an epsilon

00:14:32.630 --> 00:14:41.720 align:middle line:84%
proof, an epsilon M
proof of this statement,

00:14:41.720 --> 00:14:44.060 align:middle line:84%
then you would have taken
this and played with it

00:14:44.060 --> 00:14:48.290 align:middle line:84%
just like we did here
and gotten to 1 over n.

00:14:48.290 --> 00:14:50.278 align:middle line:84%
And therefore if this
is less than epsilon,

00:14:50.278 --> 00:14:52.070 align:middle line:84%
that would imply this
is less than epsilon.

00:14:52.070 --> 00:14:55.650 align:middle line:90%


00:14:55.650 --> 00:14:57.770 align:middle line:84%
So you would choose
capital M to be--

00:14:57.770 --> 00:15:01.170 align:middle line:84%
so that 1 over capital
M is less than epsilon.

00:15:01.170 --> 00:15:06.110 align:middle line:84%
But using these two theorems
saves us a little work

00:15:06.110 --> 00:15:06.965 align:middle line:90%
and a little time.

00:15:06.965 --> 00:15:12.610 align:middle line:90%


00:15:12.610 --> 00:15:19.220 align:middle line:84%
OK, now, so at the end
of the lecture last time,

00:15:19.220 --> 00:15:21.950 align:middle line:84%
we discussed the
notion of subsequences.

00:15:21.950 --> 00:15:27.710 align:middle line:84%
And we showed that limiting--
limits and subsequences

00:15:27.710 --> 00:15:33.350 align:middle line:84%
interact nicely, meaning if
I have a convergent sequence,

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:35.590 align:middle line:84%
then every subsequence
converges to the same thing.

00:15:35.590 --> 00:15:38.380 align:middle line:90%


00:15:38.380 --> 00:15:42.630 align:middle line:84%
So now a natural
question is, how

00:15:42.630 --> 00:15:46.500 align:middle line:84%
do limits interact with the
order of the real numbers?

00:15:46.500 --> 00:16:07.350 align:middle line:90%


00:16:07.350 --> 00:16:10.740 align:middle line:84%
R has these two fundamental
properties about it,

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:13.560 align:middle line:90%
that it's--

00:16:13.560 --> 00:16:16.060 align:middle line:84%
so first off, that it has the
least upper bound property,

00:16:16.060 --> 00:16:20.555 align:middle line:84%
and also that it's
an ordered field.

00:16:20.555 --> 00:16:21.930 align:middle line:84%
So first natural
question is, how

00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:25.560 align:middle line:84%
does this definition of
limit convergence interact

00:16:25.560 --> 00:16:29.050 align:middle line:90%
with the order?

00:16:29.050 --> 00:16:34.190 align:middle line:84%
So the first theorem states, or
this term that kind of answers

00:16:34.190 --> 00:16:38.750 align:middle line:84%
this question is the following
is that limits respect order,

00:16:38.750 --> 00:16:40.470 align:middle line:90%
basically.

00:16:40.470 --> 00:17:06.680 align:middle line:84%
So if xn, yn, are convergent
sequences and for all n,

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:10.400 align:middle line:84%
xn is less than or
equal to yn, then

00:17:10.400 --> 00:17:11.650 align:middle line:90%
what should be the conclusion?

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:13.460 align:middle line:90%
The limit as n goes to infinity.

00:17:13.460 --> 00:17:18.220 align:middle line:84%
So what I said a minute ago
as limits respect inequality.

00:17:18.220 --> 00:17:21.339 align:middle line:84%
Then I should be able to
take the limits of both sides

00:17:21.339 --> 00:17:23.349 align:middle line:90%
and still have this inequality.

00:17:23.349 --> 00:17:27.440 align:middle line:90%


00:17:27.440 --> 00:17:37.530 align:middle line:84%
Then limit as n goes to infinity
is less than or equal to limit

00:17:37.530 --> 00:17:39.180 align:middle line:84%
as n goes to
infinity of y sub n.

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:42.210 align:middle line:90%


00:17:42.210 --> 00:17:46.800 align:middle line:84%
And a simple corollary
that follows from this

00:17:46.800 --> 00:18:09.100 align:middle line:84%
is that if x sub n is
a convergent sequence,

00:18:09.100 --> 00:18:17.740 align:middle line:84%
and for all n a natural number,
you have two numbers a and b,

00:18:17.740 --> 00:18:20.950 align:middle line:84%
such that a sub n is
less than or equal to--

00:18:20.950 --> 00:18:22.750 align:middle line:84%
or a is less than or
equal to x sub n is

00:18:22.750 --> 00:18:26.850 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal
to b, then this

00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:37.980 align:middle line:84%
implies that the limit of x
sub n is also between a and b.

00:18:37.980 --> 00:18:45.420 align:middle line:84%
Let me say something
very brief about what

00:18:45.420 --> 00:18:47.130 align:middle line:90%
this says and doesn't say.

00:18:47.130 --> 00:18:49.670 align:middle line:90%


00:18:49.670 --> 00:18:50.960 align:middle line:90%
So what does this not say?

00:18:50.960 --> 00:19:04.550 align:middle line:90%


00:19:04.550 --> 00:19:07.235 align:middle line:84%
You may lose a strict
inequality, meaning what?

00:19:07.235 --> 00:19:09.830 align:middle line:90%


00:19:09.830 --> 00:19:12.500 align:middle line:84%
It can be the case that x
sub n is less than y sub

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:15.860 align:middle line:84%
n for all of n, but
the limit of x sub n

00:19:15.860 --> 00:19:18.770 align:middle line:90%
equals the limit of y sub n.

00:19:18.770 --> 00:19:23.180 align:middle line:84%
So simply having less than x
sub n less than y sub n does not

00:19:23.180 --> 00:19:28.850 align:middle line:84%
imply the limit of x sub n is
less than the limit of y sub n.

00:19:28.850 --> 00:19:30.725 align:middle line:84%
All right, so what
do I mean by this?

00:19:30.725 --> 00:19:36.280 align:middle line:90%


00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:46.078 align:middle line:84%
This does not imply that the
limit is less than y sub n.

00:19:46.078 --> 00:19:48.120 align:middle line:84%
Now, at this point in
class, I would ask somebody

00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:51.720 align:middle line:90%
to give me a counter example.

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:56.540 align:middle line:84%
So at this point, I'm going
to take a bite of my cookie

00:19:56.540 --> 00:19:57.800 align:middle line:90%
and let you think about that.

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:02.350 align:middle line:90%


00:20:02.350 --> 00:20:04.100 align:middle line:84%
I didn't have to take
a bite of my cookie.

00:20:04.100 --> 00:20:07.940 align:middle line:84%
You could have just paused the
video and thought about it.

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:12.950 align:middle line:90%


00:20:12.950 --> 00:20:15.130 align:middle line:84%
But then I wouldn't get
a bite of my cookie.

00:20:15.130 --> 00:20:23.170 align:middle line:84%
OK, so what's an example of two
sequences that satisfy this,

00:20:23.170 --> 00:20:24.240 align:middle line:90%
but don't satisfy this?

00:20:24.240 --> 00:20:30.090 align:middle line:90%


00:20:30.090 --> 00:20:41.470 align:middle line:84%
If x sub n equals 0 for all n,
and y sub n equals 1 over n,

00:20:41.470 --> 00:20:46.400 align:middle line:84%
then the x sub n is less
than y sub n for all n.

00:20:46.400 --> 00:20:50.040 align:middle line:90%


00:20:50.040 --> 00:20:55.242 align:middle line:90%
And what's the limit x sub n?

00:20:55.242 --> 00:20:56.075 align:middle line:90%
Well, that's just 0.

00:20:56.075 --> 00:21:02.490 align:middle line:90%


00:21:02.490 --> 00:21:05.130 align:middle line:84%
And before the limit of
y sub n, that's just 0.

00:21:05.130 --> 00:21:06.940 align:middle line:84%
And these two things
equal each other.

00:21:06.940 --> 00:21:10.120 align:middle line:90%
This is not less than that, OK.

00:21:10.120 --> 00:21:12.145 align:middle line:84%
So just want to make
that small point.

00:21:12.145 --> 00:21:16.760 align:middle line:90%


00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:20.600 align:middle line:84%
Could pop up as a small question
on one of the midterms--

00:21:20.600 --> 00:21:23.695 align:middle line:84%
I should say the midterm--
and possibly the final.

00:21:23.695 --> 00:21:26.760 align:middle line:90%


00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:32.286 align:middle line:90%
All right, so let's prove--

00:21:32.286 --> 00:21:35.580 align:middle line:90%
[COUGHS] let's prove 1.

00:21:35.580 --> 00:21:37.335 align:middle line:90%
2 follows immediately from one.

00:21:37.335 --> 00:21:39.870 align:middle line:90%


00:21:39.870 --> 00:21:44.480 align:middle line:84%
For two, we simply
take, for example,

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:46.210 align:middle line:84%
the upper inequality
x sub n is less

00:21:46.210 --> 00:21:47.650 align:middle line:84%
than or equal to
b, we take y sub

00:21:47.650 --> 00:21:50.890 align:middle line:90%
n to be the constant sequence b.

00:21:50.890 --> 00:21:56.830 align:middle line:84%
And for the other one, we
would take the bigger sequence

00:21:56.830 --> 00:21:58.900 align:middle line:84%
to be x sub n, and
the smaller sequence

00:21:58.900 --> 00:22:00.670 align:middle line:90%
to be the constant sequence a.

00:22:00.670 --> 00:22:05.620 align:middle line:84%
So two follows immediately from
1, so we're just going to do 1.

00:22:05.620 --> 00:22:07.510 align:middle line:84%
And we haven't done a
proof by contradiction

00:22:07.510 --> 00:22:12.530 align:middle line:84%
in a while, so why not
do it by contradiction?

00:22:12.530 --> 00:22:13.340 align:middle line:90%
OK, so the proof--

00:22:13.340 --> 00:22:18.230 align:middle line:90%


00:22:18.230 --> 00:22:19.940 align:middle line:84%
let's label these
sequences so I don't

00:22:19.940 --> 00:22:26.510 align:middle line:84%
have to write limit as n goes to
infinity, and limit of x sub n,

00:22:26.510 --> 00:22:30.900 align:middle line:84%
and limit as n goes to
infinity of y sub n so much.

00:22:30.900 --> 00:22:32.720 align:middle line:84%
So let's call their
limits x and y.

00:22:32.720 --> 00:22:38.020 align:middle line:90%


00:22:38.020 --> 00:22:39.280 align:middle line:90%
And what do we want to show?

00:22:39.280 --> 00:22:44.460 align:middle line:90%


00:22:44.460 --> 00:22:46.440 align:middle line:90%
x is less than or equal to y.

00:22:46.440 --> 00:22:48.000 align:middle line:90%
That's our goal.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.164 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to prove
this by contradiction.

00:22:50.164 --> 00:22:55.490 align:middle line:90%


00:22:55.490 --> 00:22:59.240 align:middle line:84%
That is, let's assume
y is less than x,

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:03.040 align:middle line:84%
and arrive at a false
statement, which

00:23:03.040 --> 00:23:06.580 align:middle line:84%
contradicts our setting our
assumptions that we have.

00:23:06.580 --> 00:23:10.060 align:middle line:90%
Assume y is less than x.

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:15.520 align:middle line:84%
Now, let me draw a
picture here to go along

00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:18.310 align:middle line:90%
with what's going to happen.

00:23:18.310 --> 00:23:22.550 align:middle line:90%


00:23:22.550 --> 00:23:32.050 align:middle line:84%
So if y is less than
x, all of the y sub n's

00:23:32.050 --> 00:23:35.650 align:middle line:84%
have to be near y if
I go far enough out.

00:23:35.650 --> 00:23:38.200 align:middle line:84%
And all the x sub n's
have to be near x as long

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:40.600 align:middle line:90%
as I go far enough out.

00:23:40.600 --> 00:23:43.960 align:middle line:84%
So that would
contradict eventually

00:23:43.960 --> 00:23:45.730 align:middle line:84%
the fact that the x
sub ns are supposed

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:49.480 align:middle line:84%
to be less than or equal to the
y sub n's, if y is less than x.

00:23:49.480 --> 00:23:54.340 align:middle line:84%
And let's say I
go out, let's say,

00:23:54.340 --> 00:23:57.790 align:middle line:84%
half the distance
between y and x.

00:23:57.790 --> 00:24:04.200 align:middle line:90%
So this is like the midpoint.

00:24:04.200 --> 00:24:11.660 align:middle line:84%
And all the y sub n's are here,
and all the x sub n's are here,

00:24:11.660 --> 00:24:18.760 align:middle line:84%
and the y sub n's are here, then
I cannot have x sub n less than

00:24:18.760 --> 00:24:24.470 align:middle line:84%
or equal to y sub n,
which is my assumption,

00:24:24.470 --> 00:24:28.430 align:middle line:84%
which is the assumption
in my theorem.

00:24:28.430 --> 00:24:31.340 align:middle line:84%
Now, maybe I should
have written this here.

00:24:31.340 --> 00:24:35.710 align:middle line:90%


00:24:35.710 --> 00:24:38.590 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes it's good to reiterate
what your assumptions are.

00:24:38.590 --> 00:24:41.620 align:middle line:84%
Suppose for all n, x sub n
is less than or-- y sub n.

00:24:41.620 --> 00:24:45.450 align:middle line:90%
And-- like that.

00:24:45.450 --> 00:24:48.060 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing we're
trying to show is this, OK.

00:24:48.060 --> 00:24:50.580 align:middle line:84%
So we assume the
negation of this

00:24:50.580 --> 00:24:55.350 align:middle line:84%
and arrive at a contradiction
to the things we're assuming,

00:24:55.350 --> 00:25:00.915 align:middle line:90%
or just to general true facts.

00:25:00.915 --> 00:25:07.440 align:middle line:90%


00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:10.223 align:middle line:84%
I had to add the word true on
the facts, because they're,

00:25:10.223 --> 00:25:11.640 align:middle line:84%
like I said, at
some point there's

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:14.010 align:middle line:84%
alternative facts
flying around out there.

00:25:14.010 --> 00:25:17.180 align:middle line:90%


00:25:17.180 --> 00:25:21.260 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this picture, we're
going to turn this into a proof.

00:25:21.260 --> 00:25:30.280 align:middle line:84%
So since yn converges to y,
there exists a natural number

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:39.320 align:middle line:84%
M sub 0 such that for all
n bigger than or equal to M

00:25:39.320 --> 00:25:50.527 align:middle line:84%
sub 0, y sub n minus y is
less than x minus y over 2.

00:25:50.527 --> 00:25:52.360 align:middle line:84%
Now, that's a positive
number, because we're

00:25:52.360 --> 00:25:55.510 align:middle line:90%
assuming x is bigger than y.

00:25:55.510 --> 00:26:00.610 align:middle line:84%
And by the definition of limit,
given any positive number,

00:26:00.610 --> 00:26:03.130 align:middle line:84%
I can find an integer
so that for all n bigger

00:26:03.130 --> 00:26:04.960 align:middle line:84%
than or equal to that
integer, this thing

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:06.280 align:middle line:90%
is less than that small number.

00:26:06.280 --> 00:26:07.905 align:middle line:84%
And I'm just choosing
that small number

00:26:07.905 --> 00:26:09.790 align:middle line:84%
to be this very
special small number,

00:26:09.790 --> 00:26:14.968 align:middle line:84%
because that's going to help
me arrive at a contradiction.

00:26:14.968 --> 00:26:20.590 align:middle line:90%


00:26:20.590 --> 00:26:26.260 align:middle line:84%
Since xn converges to x,
there exist M1 natural number

00:26:26.260 --> 00:26:32.700 align:middle line:84%
such that for all n bigger
than or equal to M1, x

00:26:32.700 --> 00:26:37.120 align:middle line:84%
sub n minus x is less
than the same thing.

00:26:37.120 --> 00:26:42.360 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is putting
into a precise form what

00:26:42.360 --> 00:26:44.010 align:middle line:84%
I was saying that
all the x sub n's

00:26:44.010 --> 00:26:45.870 align:middle line:90%
to be close to x eventually.

00:26:45.870 --> 00:26:48.930 align:middle line:84%
And all the y sub n's to
be close to y eventually.

00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:51.090 align:middle line:90%
And how eventually?

00:26:51.090 --> 00:26:55.860 align:middle line:84%
Well, eventually enough so
that I'm in these two disjoint

00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:59.215 align:middle line:90%
intervals, OK.

00:26:59.215 --> 00:27:04.100 align:middle line:90%


00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:11.410 align:middle line:90%
Let n be M sub 0 plus M sub 1.

00:27:11.410 --> 00:27:14.490 align:middle line:90%


00:27:14.490 --> 00:27:20.010 align:middle line:84%
Then n is bigger than
or equal to M sub 0.

00:27:20.010 --> 00:27:22.200 align:middle line:84%
And n is bigger than
or equal to M sub 1.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:27.510 align:middle line:84%
So both of these inequalities
are valid for this n

00:27:27.510 --> 00:27:29.710 align:middle line:90%
and what does this mean?

00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:33.510 align:middle line:84%
Well, then that
implies that y sub n--

00:27:33.510 --> 00:27:38.940 align:middle line:84%
so let me tack on
one more inequality.

00:27:38.940 --> 00:27:45.640 align:middle line:84%
Just by removing the
absolute values and adding y,

00:27:45.640 --> 00:27:53.660 align:middle line:84%
this tells me y sub n is
less than x plus y over 2.

00:27:53.660 --> 00:27:57.800 align:middle line:84%
And this tells me x
sub n is less than--

00:27:57.800 --> 00:28:00.320 align:middle line:90%


00:28:00.320 --> 00:28:01.520 align:middle line:90%
or the other way, sorry.

00:28:01.520 --> 00:28:09.570 align:middle line:90%


00:28:09.570 --> 00:28:14.870 align:middle line:84%
Well, we'll just
write this down here.

00:28:14.870 --> 00:28:15.370 align:middle line:90%
So

00:28:15.370 --> 00:28:25.630 align:middle line:84%
Then y sub n is less than
y plus x minus y over 2,

00:28:25.630 --> 00:28:30.640 align:middle line:84%
which equals x plus y
over 2, which equals

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:34.870 align:middle line:90%
x minus x minus y over 2.

00:28:34.870 --> 00:28:39.890 align:middle line:84%
And this is less than x sub
n by the second inequality.

00:28:39.890 --> 00:28:43.840 align:middle line:84%
So this follows from
the first inequality.

00:28:43.840 --> 00:28:48.340 align:middle line:84%
This follows from the
second inequality,

00:28:48.340 --> 00:28:50.650 align:middle line:84%
which implies for
this specific n,

00:28:50.650 --> 00:28:53.890 align:middle line:90%
y sub n is less than x sub n.

00:28:53.890 --> 00:28:56.410 align:middle line:84%
And this is a contradiction
to our assumption

00:28:56.410 --> 00:29:01.220 align:middle line:84%
that y sub n is bigger than
or equal to x sub n for all n.

00:29:01.220 --> 00:29:05.840 align:middle line:84%
So we had just found, based
on this assumption here,

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:09.628 align:middle line:84%
that we arrive at
a contradiction

00:29:09.628 --> 00:29:10.670 align:middle line:90%
to our other assumptions.

00:29:10.670 --> 00:29:14.175 align:middle line:84%
And therefore this
must be false.

00:29:14.175 --> 00:29:26.380 align:middle line:90%


00:29:26.380 --> 00:29:33.740 align:middle line:84%
So that's how limits
interact with inequalities.

00:29:33.740 --> 00:29:35.950 align:middle line:84%
So if I have two
sequences, one bigger

00:29:35.950 --> 00:29:40.570 align:middle line:84%
than the other, then the
limits respect that inequality.

00:29:40.570 --> 00:29:42.490 align:middle line:84%
That has to deal with
the order part of R

00:29:42.490 --> 00:29:43.550 align:middle line:90%
being an ordered field.

00:29:43.550 --> 00:29:47.090 align:middle line:84%
So what about the field part
of R being an ordered field?

00:29:47.090 --> 00:30:09.220 align:middle line:84%
So how does limits interact
with algebraic operations?

00:30:09.220 --> 00:30:15.790 align:middle line:90%


00:30:15.790 --> 00:30:21.240 align:middle line:84%
All right, quite
well, it turns out.

00:30:21.240 --> 00:30:22.815 align:middle line:90%
So let's in theorem.

00:30:22.815 --> 00:30:27.790 align:middle line:90%


00:30:27.790 --> 00:30:37.590 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I have two
convergence sequences,

00:30:37.590 --> 00:30:42.090 align:middle line:84%
limit as n goes to infinity
of x sub n equals x,

00:30:42.090 --> 00:30:47.430 align:middle line:84%
and limit as n goes
to infinity of y sub n

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:56.570 align:middle line:84%
equals y, then
several things hold.

00:30:56.570 --> 00:31:00.860 align:middle line:84%
The first is that, again,
you should kind of read this

00:31:00.860 --> 00:31:04.910 align:middle line:84%
as two statements written
in one, limit as n

00:31:04.910 --> 00:31:08.510 align:middle line:84%
goes to infinity of
x sub n plus y sub n.

00:31:08.510 --> 00:31:11.150 align:middle line:84%
So this is a new
sequence that I formed

00:31:11.150 --> 00:31:14.270 align:middle line:84%
by just taking the term-by-term
sum of these two things.

00:31:14.270 --> 00:31:17.710 align:middle line:90%


00:31:17.710 --> 00:31:19.960 align:middle line:84%
This sequence, this new
sequence is convergent.

00:31:19.960 --> 00:31:24.700 align:middle line:84%
And the limit equals the
sum of the limits, OK?

00:31:24.700 --> 00:31:28.130 align:middle line:90%


00:31:28.130 --> 00:31:35.870 align:middle line:84%
The second is, for
all c in R, the limit

00:31:35.870 --> 00:31:39.170 align:middle line:84%
as n goes to infinity of
the new sequence obtained

00:31:39.170 --> 00:31:43.780 align:middle line:84%
by taking every entry
of the sequence x sub n

00:31:43.780 --> 00:31:45.820 align:middle line:84%
and multiplying it
by this fixed number

00:31:45.820 --> 00:31:53.120 align:middle line:84%
c, the limit of that product
is the product of c and x.

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:56.990 align:middle line:84%
So limits respect what one would
call scalar multiplication.

00:31:56.990 --> 00:32:05.250 align:middle line:90%


00:32:05.250 --> 00:32:07.950 align:middle line:84%
But we could be more
general than that.

00:32:07.950 --> 00:32:11.160 align:middle line:84%
c you can think of
as just one example

00:32:11.160 --> 00:32:14.410 align:middle line:84%
of a convergent sequence,
just a constant sequence.

00:32:14.410 --> 00:32:17.100 align:middle line:84%
But, in general, we
have that the product

00:32:17.100 --> 00:32:20.640 align:middle line:84%
of two convergent
sequences is convergent.

00:32:20.640 --> 00:32:23.895 align:middle line:84%
And the limit of the product
is the product of the limit.

00:32:23.895 --> 00:32:27.870 align:middle line:90%


00:32:27.870 --> 00:32:30.610 align:middle line:84%
And, finally, if we
have something for--

00:32:30.610 --> 00:32:32.700 align:middle line:90%
write it over here--

00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:36.540 align:middle line:84%
if we have something
for a product,

00:32:36.540 --> 00:32:39.300 align:middle line:84%
then perhaps we have
something by quotient.

00:32:39.300 --> 00:32:41.530 align:middle line:84%
