01:03:46.805 --> 01:03:49.180 align:middle line:84%
So then that's going to be
the difference of the squares.

01:03:49.180 --> 01:03:52.480 align:middle line:90%
So that's equal to--

01:03:52.480 --> 01:03:55.460 align:middle line:84%
over-- and, again, these
are positive numbers

01:03:55.460 --> 01:03:59.770 align:middle line:84%
so that they come out
of the absolute value.

01:03:59.770 --> 01:04:02.400 align:middle line:90%
And this is non-negative.

01:04:02.400 --> 01:04:05.820 align:middle line:84%
So, in fact, it's only making
things bigger on the bottom

01:04:05.820 --> 01:04:08.290 align:middle line:84%
and therefore things
smaller overall.

01:04:08.290 --> 01:04:11.430 align:middle line:84%
So this is less
than or equal to--

01:04:11.430 --> 01:04:13.875 align:middle line:84%
just if I replace this
by square root of x.

01:04:13.875 --> 01:04:17.990 align:middle line:90%


01:04:17.990 --> 01:04:21.620 align:middle line:90%
So what did I prove?

01:04:21.620 --> 01:04:32.860 align:middle line:90%


01:04:32.860 --> 01:04:34.750 align:middle line:90%
1 over square root of x--

01:04:34.750 --> 01:04:37.780 align:middle line:90%


01:04:37.780 --> 01:04:38.380 align:middle line:90%
all right.

01:04:38.380 --> 01:04:42.010 align:middle line:84%
And so by assumption,
x sub n converges to x.

01:04:42.010 --> 01:04:43.690 align:middle line:90%
So this goes to 0.

01:04:43.690 --> 01:04:45.970 align:middle line:84%
This is a fixed
number multiplied

01:04:45.970 --> 01:04:47.230 align:middle line:90%
by this thing going to 0.

01:04:47.230 --> 01:04:50.310 align:middle line:84%
So by number 2
and the theorem we

01:04:50.310 --> 01:04:54.190 align:middle line:84%
proved before, this whole
product converges to 0.

01:04:54.190 --> 01:04:56.650 align:middle line:84%
So, and of course
this converges to 0.

01:04:56.650 --> 01:04:59.110 align:middle line:84%
So this thing in the
middle must converge to 0

01:04:59.110 --> 01:05:00.070 align:middle line:90%
by the squeeze theorem.

01:05:00.070 --> 01:05:29.110 align:middle line:90%


01:05:29.110 --> 01:05:39.440 align:middle line:90%
So that's the square root.

01:05:39.440 --> 01:06:04.995 align:middle line:90%
And let me just remark that--

01:06:04.995 --> 01:06:08.320 align:middle line:90%


01:06:08.320 --> 01:06:12.160 align:middle line:84%
so this number 3 up here,
that the limit of the product

01:06:12.160 --> 01:06:14.590 align:middle line:84%
is a product of the
limits, this thus

01:06:14.590 --> 01:06:18.740 align:middle line:84%
implies that the limit of xn
squared converges to x squared.

01:06:18.740 --> 01:06:21.490 align:middle line:84%
So the square of
x sub n converges

01:06:21.490 --> 01:06:23.560 align:middle line:90%
to the square of the limit.

01:06:23.560 --> 01:06:28.030 align:middle line:84%
And by induction, you can show
that the cube fourth power,

01:06:28.030 --> 01:06:31.330 align:middle line:84%
fifth power of x sub n
converges to the fourth power,

01:06:31.330 --> 01:06:32.530 align:middle line:90%
fifth power of x.

01:06:32.530 --> 01:06:38.260 align:middle line:84%
And not only that,
you can also prove--

01:06:38.260 --> 01:06:40.282 align:middle line:90%
so I'm not going to do this.

01:06:40.282 --> 01:06:41.990 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not going to
force you to either.

01:06:41.990 --> 01:06:45.023 align:middle line:84%
But just know these
as facts, that I

01:06:45.023 --> 01:06:46.690 align:middle line:84%
don't have to just
take the square root,

01:06:46.690 --> 01:06:48.460 align:middle line:90%
I could take the k-th root.

01:06:48.460 --> 01:06:51.150 align:middle line:90%


01:06:51.150 --> 01:06:53.820 align:middle line:84%
And this statement still
is true that if x sub n is

01:06:53.820 --> 01:06:58.320 align:middle line:84%
bigger than or equal to 0 for
all n, and I have a limit,

01:06:58.320 --> 01:07:00.930 align:middle line:84%
then the k-th root
of x sub n converges

01:07:00.930 --> 01:07:02.580 align:middle line:90%
to the k-th root of x.

01:07:02.580 --> 01:07:08.340 align:middle line:90%


01:07:08.340 --> 01:07:12.850 align:middle line:84%
So the final theorem
we'll prove for today,

01:07:12.850 --> 01:07:22.440 align:middle line:84%
which will conclude our facts
about limits, is we have--

01:07:22.440 --> 01:07:24.240 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we've been
using this all along,

01:07:24.240 --> 01:07:27.060 align:middle line:84%
although I haven't made
special attention about it.

01:07:27.060 --> 01:07:29.160 align:middle line:84%
The real numbers
there, this, again,

01:07:29.160 --> 01:07:31.380 align:middle line:84%
like I said, an ordered
field with a least upper

01:07:31.380 --> 01:07:32.760 align:middle line:90%
bound property.

01:07:32.760 --> 01:07:38.790 align:middle line:84%
So we've seen how limits
interact with this structure

01:07:38.790 --> 01:07:39.750 align:middle line:90%
of the real numbers.

01:07:39.750 --> 01:07:41.940 align:middle line:84%
But they also have a
distance associated

01:07:41.940 --> 01:07:43.780 align:middle line:90%
to them, the absolute value.

01:07:43.780 --> 01:07:47.460 align:middle line:84%
The distance from
two numbers a and b

01:07:47.460 --> 01:07:49.440 align:middle line:84%
is the absolute
value of a minus b.

01:07:49.440 --> 01:07:52.650 align:middle line:90%


01:07:52.650 --> 01:07:56.500 align:middle line:84%
Or the distance
from a number to 0

01:07:56.500 --> 01:07:58.940 align:middle line:84%
is just the absolute
value of that number.

01:07:58.940 --> 01:08:03.250 align:middle line:84%
So one could ask,
how does the limit

01:08:03.250 --> 01:08:05.620 align:middle line:84%
interact with this
additional structure

01:08:05.620 --> 01:08:08.410 align:middle line:90%
of the absolute value?

01:08:08.410 --> 01:08:13.420 align:middle line:84%
And so just like everything's
been good so far with limits,

01:08:13.420 --> 01:08:15.580 align:middle line:84%
it's the, same with the
absolute value namely

01:08:15.580 --> 01:08:17.635 align:middle line:84%
that limits respect
absolute value.

01:08:17.635 --> 01:08:21.970 align:middle line:90%


01:08:21.970 --> 01:08:42.810 align:middle line:84%
So if x sub n is
convergent sequence,

01:08:42.810 --> 01:08:52.410 align:middle line:84%
the limit x, then the
sequence of absolute values

01:08:52.410 --> 01:08:53.759 align:middle line:90%
is also a convergent sequence.

01:08:53.759 --> 01:09:06.210 align:middle line:90%


01:09:06.210 --> 01:09:12.270 align:middle line:84%
And the limit as n goes to
infinity of the absolute values

01:09:12.270 --> 01:09:16.410 align:middle line:84%
equals the absolute
value of the limit.

01:09:16.410 --> 01:09:22.740 align:middle line:84%
Now let me, again, let's try
to think a little more deeply

01:09:22.740 --> 01:09:25.390 align:middle line:90%
about this real quick.

01:09:25.390 --> 01:09:27.810 align:middle line:84%
If I have a convergence
sequence and the absolute values

01:09:27.810 --> 01:09:31.040 align:middle line:84%
converge, does
the converse hold?

01:09:31.040 --> 01:09:33.229 align:middle line:84%
If the absolute values
converge, does this

01:09:33.229 --> 01:09:35.540 align:middle line:84%
imply that the original
sequence converges?

01:09:35.540 --> 01:09:38.407 align:middle line:84%
And the answer
is, of course, no.

01:09:38.407 --> 01:09:39.240 align:middle line:90%
Well, not of course.

01:09:39.240 --> 01:09:41.323 align:middle line:84%
I didn't even give you a
minute to think about it.

01:09:41.323 --> 01:09:45.636 align:middle line:84%
But why is the
converse not true?

01:09:45.636 --> 01:09:46.844 align:middle line:90%
So let me make this a remark.

01:09:46.844 --> 01:09:58.600 align:middle line:90%


01:09:58.600 --> 01:10:01.930 align:middle line:84%
Converse is not true
because you could look at x

01:10:01.930 --> 01:10:03.922 align:middle line:90%
sub n equals minus 1 to the n.

01:10:03.922 --> 01:10:06.480 align:middle line:90%


01:10:06.480 --> 01:10:14.280 align:middle line:84%
Then the absolute
values of these guys

01:10:14.280 --> 01:10:16.890 align:middle line:84%
converges, but the original
sequence does not converge.

01:10:16.890 --> 01:10:25.030 align:middle line:90%


01:10:25.030 --> 01:10:32.190 align:middle line:84%
So this is a one-way
street for convergence

01:10:32.190 --> 01:10:33.990 align:middle line:84%
and the convergence of
the absolute values.

01:10:33.990 --> 01:10:44.350 align:middle line:90%


01:10:44.350 --> 01:10:45.920 align:middle line:84%
So before I prove
this theorem, let

01:10:45.920 --> 01:10:53.983 align:middle line:84%
me just prove a quick
inequality which

01:10:53.983 --> 01:10:56.150 align:middle line:84%
I think I said I was going
to put on the assignment,

01:10:56.150 --> 01:10:57.858 align:middle line:84%
and then forgot to
put on the assignment.

01:10:57.858 --> 01:10:59.600 align:middle line:90%
But you should know it.

01:10:59.600 --> 01:11:07.400 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem is the
reverse triangle inequality

01:11:07.400 --> 01:11:12.710 align:middle line:84%
which states for all a, b real
number, the absolute value

01:11:12.710 --> 01:11:15.980 align:middle line:84%
of the difference in
absolute values is less than

01:11:15.980 --> 01:11:19.810 align:middle line:84%
or equal to the absolute
value of the difference.

01:11:19.810 --> 01:11:28.360 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the proof of this
reverse triangle inequality

01:11:28.360 --> 01:11:31.280 align:middle line:84%
just uses the original
triangle inequality.

01:11:31.280 --> 01:11:39.060 align:middle line:84%
So absolute value of a, this
is equal to the absolute value

01:11:39.060 --> 01:11:42.320 align:middle line:90%
of a minus b plus b.

01:11:42.320 --> 01:11:45.230 align:middle line:84%
And this is less than or
equal to the absolute value

01:11:45.230 --> 01:11:50.420 align:middle line:84%
of a minus b plus
absolute value of b.

01:11:50.420 --> 01:11:55.970 align:middle line:84%
And thus the absolute value of
a minus the absolute value of b

01:11:55.970 --> 01:12:00.350 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to the
absolute value of a minus b.

01:12:00.350 --> 01:12:04.040 align:middle line:84%
Now, these are just two
numbers, I mean two letters,

01:12:04.040 --> 01:12:04.925 align:middle line:90%
reverse the letters.

01:12:04.925 --> 01:12:11.580 align:middle line:90%


01:12:11.580 --> 01:12:15.570 align:middle line:84%
In this argument replace
a with b and b with a.

01:12:15.570 --> 01:12:20.060 align:middle line:84%
So then I get b minus
the absolute value.

01:12:20.060 --> 01:12:22.290 align:middle line:84%
The absolute value of b
minus the absolute value of a

01:12:22.290 --> 01:12:28.860 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to the
absolute value of b minus a,

01:12:28.860 --> 01:12:30.000 align:middle line:90%
which is the same as this.

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:34.080 align:middle line:90%


01:12:34.080 --> 01:12:40.260 align:middle line:84%
And therefore-- let me
multiply through by minus 1,

01:12:40.260 --> 01:12:41.430 align:middle line:90%
and that tells me--

01:12:41.430 --> 01:12:47.650 align:middle line:90%


01:12:47.650 --> 01:12:51.550 align:middle line:84%
OK, so I have this is less than
or equal to the absolute value

01:12:51.550 --> 01:12:52.600 align:middle line:90%
of a minus b.

01:12:52.600 --> 01:12:54.220 align:middle line:84%
I also have it's
bigger than or equal

01:12:54.220 --> 01:12:56.440 align:middle line:84%
to minus the absolute
value of a minus b.

01:12:56.440 --> 01:13:00.810 align:middle line:90%


01:13:00.810 --> 01:13:03.870 align:middle line:84%
And therefore the
absolute value of a minus

01:13:03.870 --> 01:13:10.470 align:middle line:84%
the absolute value of b is less
than or equal to absolute value

01:13:10.470 --> 01:13:11.370 align:middle line:90%
of a minus b.

01:13:11.370 --> 01:13:17.680 align:middle line:90%


01:13:17.680 --> 01:13:19.840 align:middle line:84%
So I it's taboo to write
on the very back board,

01:13:19.840 --> 01:13:22.450 align:middle line:90%
but I'm going to do it anyway.

01:13:22.450 --> 01:13:24.970 align:middle line:84%
So that was the proof of the
reverse triangle inequality.

01:13:24.970 --> 01:13:29.910 align:middle line:84%
Here's the proof of
the theorem before it.

01:13:29.910 --> 01:13:33.230 align:middle line:84%
It just follows from the
reverse triangle inequality

01:13:33.230 --> 01:13:38.050 align:middle line:84%
and that combination of those
two theorems over there.

01:13:38.050 --> 01:13:42.150 align:middle line:90%


01:13:42.150 --> 01:13:45.240 align:middle line:84%
We have that the
absolute value of x sub n

01:13:45.240 --> 01:13:48.090 align:middle line:90%
minus the absolute value of x.

01:13:48.090 --> 01:13:50.760 align:middle line:84%
This is less than or equal
to, by the reverse triangle

01:13:50.760 --> 01:13:54.000 align:middle line:84%
inequality, the absolute
value of x sub n minus x.

01:13:54.000 --> 01:13:57.340 align:middle line:90%


01:13:57.340 --> 01:14:05.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is by the reverse
triangle inequality.

01:14:05.650 --> 01:14:10.390 align:middle line:84%
And by assumption,
this converges to 0

01:14:10.390 --> 01:14:11.770 align:middle line:90%
as n goes to infinity.

01:14:11.770 --> 01:14:18.730 align:middle line:90%


01:14:18.730 --> 01:14:27.820 align:middle line:84%
So by the squeeze
theorem, this goes to 0.

01:14:27.820 --> 01:14:33.500 align:middle line:84%
And therefore the absolute
value of x sub n converges

01:14:33.500 --> 01:14:37.180 align:middle line:90%
to the absolute value of x.

01:14:37.180 --> 01:14:44.470 align:middle line:84%
And that's it for that proof for
this lecture and for this week.

01:14:44.470 --> 01:14:52.110 align:middle line:90%